[1] Case updates

- Sat 19 Jan 2019. Epidemiological situation report, DRC Ministry of Health
[in French, machine trans., abridged, edited]
https://us13.campaign-archive.com/?u=89e5755d2cca4840b1af93176&id=2b3d226b45

- Since the beginning of the epidemic, the cumulative number of cases is 685, of which 636 are confirmed and 49 are probable. In total, there were 416 deaths (367 confirmed and 49 probable) and 244 people cured.
- 142 suspected cases under investigation.
- 5 new confirmed cases, including 4 in Katwa and 1 in Beni. The case of Beni is the 19-day-old baby of the confirmed case reported in the bulletin of 18 Jan 2019.
- 2 new deaths of confirmed cases (all community deaths) in Katwa.
- 1 new person healed out of Butembo CTE.

News of the response
------------------
Epidemiological situation in Katwa
- The health zones of Katwa and Butembo are the main current outbreaks of the epidemic, which reported 65% of new confirmed cases recorded in the last 21 days (58/89).
- The main difficulty in Katwa is the reluctance of relatives of confirmed cases. The majority of new confirmed cases identified in Katwa are reluctant contacts who have refused vaccination and follow-up of contacts. Thus, the last 10 confirmed cases of Katwa, in the Muchanga health area, have family or neighborhood links.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Mary Marshall

[Helen Branswell (https://twitter.com/HelenBranswell):
A 19-day-old baby is among the 5 new #Ebola cases the #DRC @MinSanteRDC is reporting today. The infant's mother is a confirmed case. There are also +2 deaths -- community deaths -- today, bringing the outbreak totals to 685 cases & 416 deaths.

Four of today's cases & both deaths occurred at Katwa, a health zone that's adjacent to Butembo, a large (+1 million) city. Butembo-Katwa is the current #Ebola hotspot & there's a huge amount of resistance there to containment measures like vaccination, contact monitoring, etc.]

[It appears to be cultural and social aspects that are perpetuating the outbreak in the DRC even when the new medical countermeasures that were not available to West Africa could stop the spread of the virus. The rVSV-ZEBOV vaccine appears to be preventing an explosion of cases, but when those who need to be vaccinated, i.e. the contacts of infected individuals, cannot be identified, the virus will continue to spread. Efforts have been made to reach the traditional doctors and the locals, but the fear and distrust continue. Ebola treatment centers are being added; a 9th center just opened in Makayanga (see below), but there continue to be fatal cases following treatment at community clinics. The 19-day old baby might have been able to be saved had the mother presented at an Ebola treatment center before birth, although it may have been too late. Further, at the community clinics, others are exposed to the infectious patient. This is further exacerbated by the movement of the population due to ongoing unrest in the country. This outbreak is a major scientific and social challenge that calls for innovative approaches to engaging the communities and a lot of support. - Mod.LK]

- Fri 18 Jan 2019. Epidemiological situation report, DRC Ministry of Health
[in French, machine trans., abridged, edited]
https://us13.campaign-archive.com/?u=89e5755d2cca4840b1af93176&id=45b7929f20

The epidemiological situation of the Ebola virus disease dated 17 Jan 2019:
- Since the beginning of the epidemic, the cumulative number of cases is 680, of which 631 are confirmed and 49 are probable.
In total, there were 414 deaths (365 confirmed and 49 probable) and 243 people cured.
- 209 suspected cases under investigation.
- 12 new confirmed cases, including 6 in Katwa, 2 in Butembo, 1 in Musienene, 1 in Kayina, 1 in Kyondo and 1 in Beni.
- 4 new confirmed deaths including 3 community deaths in Katwa and 1 hospital death in Beni.
- 1 new person healed out of Butembo CTE.

News of the response
-----------------
Medical care
- On Thu 17 Jan 2019, the Governor of Ituri Province, Pacific Keta, inaugurated a new Ebola Treatment Center (ETC) and a laboratory in Makayanga (Komanda). This is the 9th CTE built during this 10th Ebola epidemic after those of Beni, Bunia, Butembo, Goma, Katwa, Mandima, Mangina and Tchomia. This new 28-bed CTE, the 3rd in the province of Ituri, is designed to treat and isolate confirmed and suspected cases of Ebola from the Komanda Health Zone and surrounding areas.

Vaccination
- Since vaccination began on 8 Aug 2018, 61 682 people have been vaccinated, including 20 012 in Beni, 13 123 in Katwa, 6796 in Butembo, 5751 in Mabalako, 2433 in Kalunguta, 2080 in Komanda, 1751 in Goma, 1663 in Mandima, 1406 in Oicha, 1157 in Karisimbi, 877 in Vuhovi, 774 in Kyondo, 750 in Masereka, 700 in Lubero, 599 in Mutwanga, 442 in Musienene, 434 in Bunia, 355 in Tchomia, 167 in Nyankunde, 120 in Biena, 99 in Nyiragongo, 63 in Alimbongo, 57 in Kirotshe, and 13 in Kisangani.

- The only vaccine to be used in this outbreak is the rVSV-ZEBOV vaccine, manufactured by the pharmaceutical group Merck, following approval by the Ethics Committee in its decision of 19 May 2018.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteurs Kunihiko Iizuka and Mary Marshall

